`, and `5^(th)` buildings as that would form `\"0**11**\"` which is **not** allowed due to having two consecutive buildings of the same type.\n\nReturn *the **number of valid ways** to select 3 buildings.*\n\n**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":1,"text":"Input: s = \"001101\"\nOutput: 6\nExplanation: \nThe following sets of indices selected are valid:\n- [0,2,4] from \"001101\" forms \"010\"\n- [0,3,4] from \"001101\" forms \"010\"\n- [1,2,4] from \"001101\" forms \"010\"\n- [1,3,4] from \"001101\" forms \"010\"\n- [2,4,5] from \"001101\" forms \"101\"\n- [3,4,5] from \"001101\" forms \"101\"\nNo other selection is valid. Thus, there are 6 total ways.","type":"code"},{"sequence":2,"text":"**Example 2:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":3,"text":"Input: s = \"11100\"\nOutput: 0\nExplanation: It can be shown that there are no valid selections.","type":"code"},{"sequence":4,"text":"**Constraints:**\n\n- `3 <= s.length <= 10⁵`\n\n- `s[i]` is either `'0'` or `'1'`.","type":"text"}],"contentHtml":"","contentHtmlLocal":"","databaseEntry":{"categories":["String","Dynamic Programming","Prefix Sum"],"createdAt":0,"difficulty":"Medium","lastRevisionAt":0,"problem":"You are given a **0-indexed** binary string `s` which represents the types of buildings along a street where:\n\n- `s[i] = '0'` denotes that the `i^(th)` building is an office and\n\n- `s[i] = '1'` denotes that the `i^(th)` building is a restaurant.\n\nAs a city official, you would like to **select** 3 buildings for random inspection. However, to ensure variety, **no two consecutive** buildings out of the **selected** buildings can be of the same type.\n\n- For example, given `s = \"0**0**1**1**0**1**\"`, we cannot select the `1^(st)`, `3^(rd)`, and `5^(th)` buildings as that would form `\"0**11**\"` which is **not** allowed due to having two consecutive buildings of the same type.\n\nReturn *the **number of valid ways** to select 3 buildings.*\n\n**Example 1:**\n\nInput: s = \"001101\"\nOutput: 6\nExplanation: \n