een `00` and `23`, and `MM` is between `00` and `59`. The earliest 24-hour time is `00:00`, and the latest is `23:59`.\n\nIn one operation you can increase the time `current` by `1`, `5`, `15`, or `60` minutes. You can perform this operation **any** number of times.\n\nReturn *the **minimum number of operations** needed to convert *`current`* to *`correct`.\n\n**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":1,"text":"Input: current = \"02:30\", correct = \"04:35\"\nOutput: 3\nExplanation:\nWe can convert current to correct in 3 operations as follows:\n- Add 60 minutes to current. current becomes \"03:30\".\n- Add 60 minutes to current. current becomes \"04:30\".\n- Add 5 minutes to current. current becomes \"04:35\".\nIt can be proven that it is not possible to convert current to correct in fewer than 3 operations.","type":"code"},{"sequence":2,"text":"**Example 2:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":3,"text":"Input: current = \"11:00\", correct = \"11:01\"\nOutput: 1\nExplanation: We only have to add one minute to current, so the minimum number of operations needed is 1.","type":"code"},{"sequence":4,"text":"**Constraints:**\n\n- `current` and `correct` are in the format `\"HH:MM\"`\n\n- `current <= correct`","type":"text"}],"contentHtml":"","contentHtmlLocal":"","databaseEntry":{"categories":["String","Greedy"],"createdAt":0,"difficulty":"Easy","lastRevisionAt":0,"problem":"You are given two strings `current` and `correct` representing two **24-hour times**.\n\n24-hour times are formatted as `\"HH:MM\"`, where `HH` is between `00` and `23`, and `MM` is between `00` and `59`. The earliest 24-hour time is `00:00`, and the latest is `23:59`.\n\nIn one operation you can increase the time `current` by `1`, `5`, `15`, or `60` minutes. You can perform this operation **any** number of times.\n\nReturn *the **minimum number of operations** needed to convert *`current`* to *`correct`.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\nInput: current = \"02:30\", correct = \"04:35\"\nOutput: 3\nExplanation:\nWe can convert current to correct in 3 operations as follows:\n- Add 60 minutes to current. current becomes \"03:30\".\n- Add 60 minutes to current. current becomes \"04:30\".\n- Add 5 minutes to current. current becomes \"04:35\".\nIt can be proven that it is not possible to convert current to correct in fewer than 3 operations.\n\n**Example 2:**\n\nInput: current = \"11:00\", correct = \"11:01\"\nOutput: 1\nExplanation: We only have to add one minute to current, so the minimum number of operations needed is 1.\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `current` and `correct` are in the format `\"HH:MM\"`\n\n- `current <= correct`","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/minimum-number-of-operations-to-convert-time/","problemName":"Minimum Number of Operations to Convert Time","problemNumber":2224,"revisionAnchorAt":0,"revisionCount":0,"revisionDates":[],"revisionPlanHours":[1,24,168,336,672],"solutionCode":"","testCases":"","updatedAt":0},"descriptionBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"You are given two strings `current` and `correct` representing two **24-hour times**.\n\n24-hour times are formatted as `\"HH:MM\"`, where `HH` is between `00` and `23`, and `MM` is between `00` and `59`. The earliest 24-hour time is `00:00`, and the latest is `23:59`.\n\nIn one operation you can increase the time `current` by `1`, `5`, `15`, or `60` minutes. You can perform this operation **any** number of times.\n\nReturn *the **minimum number of operations** needed to convert *`current`* to *`correct`.\n\n**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":1,"text":"Input: current = \"02:30\", correct = \"04:35\"\nOutput: 3\nExplanation:\nWe can convert current to correct in 3 operations as follows:\n- Add 60 minutes to current. current becomes \"03:30\".\n- Add 60 minutes to current. current becomes \"04:30\".\n- Add 5 minutes to current. current becomes \"04:35\".\nIt can be proven that it is not possible to convert current to correct in fewer than 3 operations.","type":"code"},{"sequence":2,"text":"**Example 2:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":3,"text":"Input: current = \"11:00\", correct = \"11:01\"\nOutput: 1\nExplanation: We only have to add one minute to current, so the minimum number of operations needed is 1.","type":"code"},{"sequence":4,"text":"**Constraints:**\n\n- `current` and `correct` are in the format `\"HH:MM\"`\n\n- `current <= correct`","type":"text"}],"difficulty":"Easy","examples":[],"paidOnly":false,"problem":"You are given two strings `current` and `correct` representing two **24-hour times**.\n\n24-hour times are formatted as `\"HH:MM\"`, where `HH` is between `00` and `23`, and `MM` is between `00` and `59`. The earliest 24-hour time is `00:00`, and the latest is `23:59`.\n\nIn one operation you can increase the time `current` by `1`, `5`, `15`, or `60` minutes. You can perform this operation **any** number of times.\n\nReturn *the **minimum number of operations** needed to convert *`current`* to *`correct`.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\nInput: current = \"02:30\", correct = \"04:35\"\nOutput: 3\nExplanation:\nWe can convert current to correct in 3 operations as follows:\n- Add 60 minutes to current. current becomes \"03:30\".\n- Add 60 minutes to current. current becomes \"04:30\".\n- Add 5 minutes to current. current becomes \"04:35\".\nIt can be proven that it is not possible to convert current to correct in fewer than 3 operations.\n\n**Example 2:**\n\nInput: current = \"11:00\", correct = \"11:01\"\nOutput: 1\nExplanation: We only have to add one minute to current, so the minimum number of operations needed is 1.\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `current` and `correct` are in the format `\"HH:MM\"`\n\n- `current <= correct`","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/minimum-number-of-operations-to-convert-time/","problemName":"Minimum Number of Operations to Convert Time","problemNumber":2224,"problemSlug":"minimum-number-of-operations-to-convert-time","schemaVersion":2,"sequenceIndex":2224,"solutionApproaches":[]},{"assets":[],"categories":["Array","Hash Ta